{"attack":true,"case":"The target's fourth forbidden case (the one under trial) violates std-crit-design clause (2) and the honesty clause. The case posits an 'adaptive-confidence variant' arm and forbids the outcome 'adaptive arm shows no additional gain over the non-adaptive arm.' But the claim, mechanism, and scope define the entire theory purely in terms of base error e, ensemble size k, critic precision p, and critic recall r — there is no variable, threshold, or predicted effect for an 'adaptive-confidence' variant. The proposal never states what adaptive confidence is, how it modulates p or r, or what measurable gain it should produce. Consequently the forbidden condition ('adaptive arm shows no additional gain') is not a pre-registered, theory-derived refutation point; it is an ad hoc post-hoc bar ('make the adaptive variant show extra gain') that cannot falsify the precision-threshold model either way. If the adaptive variant simply applies the same p and r, the model predicts identical scores and the 'forbidden' outcome is mandatory, not refuting; if it changes p or r, the proposal gives no formula to predict the delta, so the case is unmeasurable as a refutation of the stated claim. This is exactly the aspirational, non-operationalized design the standard forbids. The case also does not specify how the repository's validation harness would measure an 'adaptive-confidence' arm that is not defined in the claim's variables, violating the requirement that forbidden cases be measurable by rerunning the harness.","counterexample":null}